# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a-o-broadley
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] The **United Kingdom Census 1911** of 2 April 1911 was the 12th nationwide census conducted in the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] The total population of the United Kingdom was approximately 45,221,000, with 36,070,000 recorded in England and Wales, 4,761,000 in Scotland, and 4,390,000 in Ireland.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] The census covered England, Wales, Scotland, the Channel Islands, and ships of the Royal Navy at sea and in ports abroad.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] The Census of Ireland, 1911 was carried out on the same day but the records are held separately by the National Archives of Ireland.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] The 1911 census was the first to ask about nationality, the duration of current marriage, number of children born within that marriage, number of living children and the number of any children who had died.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] It was the first to record full details of British Army personnel stationed overseas instead of requiring just a simple headcount.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] It was also the first census where the forms were completed by the respondents and retained rather than being copied into the enumeration books.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] This census was subject to protests by women seeking the right to vote in the UK.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] Several suffragette organisations urged women and supporters of women's enfranchisement to boycott the census.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] The movement was also advertised by suffragist and writer Laurence Housman through a series of articles published in *The Vote*, in which he argued for the reasoning and tactical benefits of the proposal.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] He also wrote fiction supporting the movement, setting this series in a potential future where the boycott went well.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] Some suffragettes like Joan Cather refused to fill in the forms, which were returned with sloganned stickers, such as "Votes for Women" or other slogans on their census returns.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] Her husband supported her position as he annotated the Census form that he had 'conscientious scruples' as head of household to note any 'female occupants' to avoid the census statistics being used by legislators for 'further vexatious legislation' against women 'in which they have no voice'.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] He went on to say he would provide the information if the Conciliation Committee Bill passed into law.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] The Registrar did however note two females as 'the probable number'.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] Other suffragettes evaded the census by hiding overnight so that they could not be counted.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] In places throughout the UK, activists organised rallies or threw parties for suffragettes away from home, some for recreation, others for making political statements.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] Dorothy Evans organised parties for census boycotters in Birmingham, while Annie Kenney organised the census boycott in Bristol, and Lillian Dove-Willcox organised the boycott in Trowbridge.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] Margaret Nevinson was at home in Downside Crescent in London, harbouring an undetermined number of women who did not wish to be included in the census; an official copy of the census schedule survives, with a note on the refusals and their reason.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] Her husband and fellow suffragist Henry, deliberately absent from home, went skating, dining with Evelyn Sharp and other census resisters.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] Most famously, Emily Davison hid herself in a cupboard in the House of Commons at the Palace of Westminster overnight, becoming, when found, listed on the form as an occupant of the building.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] She could thus be enumerated in Parliament.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] The impact of the census boycott is unclear.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] Margaret Nevinson wrote in the *Suffrage Annual* that some thousands of women did not appear in the census for that reason.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] The estimate by Agnes Metcalfe that the figure was at least 100,000 is doubted.
[src:a-o-broadley/1911-united-kingdom-census] The census data was published online on a subscription basis in 2009.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-breeze-harper] Harper attributes her initial interest in practicing veganism to the influence of the work of Dick Gregory in connecting diet to the liberation struggle of marginalized groups, and to Afrocentric, raw foodist Queen Afua.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-breeze-harper] In 2015, Harper organized a conference, *The Vegan Praxis of Black Lives Matters*, to discuss intersectional issues concerning veganism and the Black Lives Matter movement.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-breeze-harper] In the same year, Harper joined the advisory board for *Black Vegans Rock*.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-breeze-harper] Harper was the Humane Party's vice-presidential nominee for the 2016 U.S. presidential election.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] In 1893, Cole prepared a set of vegetarian menus that received high commendation at the Universal Cookery Exhibition.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] The menus were later published as "Menus for a Week in November" in Rachel Swain's *Swain Cookery* and in Florence I.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] Nicholson's *The Jubilee Cookery Book: Vegetarian Recipes*.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] Cole worked in several London vegetarian organisations.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] Tovey in founding the Battersea, Clapham and Wandsworth Vegetarian Society, with A.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] She was a committee member of the Women's Vegetarian Union and gave a cookery lesson for the union at the offices of the Vegetarian Federal Union in 1898.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] According to James Gregory, Cole worked as an assistant to Nicholson and later to Charlotte Despard.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] She succeeded Nicholson as editor of *The Children's Realm*.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] By 1914, she was honorary secretary of the Vegetarian Federal Union.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] Cole gave public talks and demonstrations on vegetarian cookery.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] In 1910, as secretary of the West London Vegetarian Society, she gave a cookery demonstration at a vegetarian dinner held by the society at Pirbright Hall, Southfields.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] In 1913, as honorary secretary of the London Vegetarian Society, she spoke on "What is Vegetarianism" at a meeting at the Adult School in Sutton.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] In July 1915, *The Jewish Chronicle* published an interview with Cole, then secretary of the London Vegetarian Association, on vegetarianism and Jewish dietary practice.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] She argued that a vegetarian diet was compatible with Jewish religious observance and discussed food economy during the First World War.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] In 1917, when described as a former organising secretary of the London Vegetarian Association, she gave cookery demonstrations for the Food and Cookery Association in Southampton, where she presented vegetarian menus and methods for reducing food waste.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] Cole was listed as secretary of the Children's Dinner Fund in 1916.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] Hilda Kean writes that Nicholson established the fund for underfed children, distributing cheap meals of vegetable soup, wholemeal bread, and wholemeal currant bread.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-m-cole] In 1921, Cole was honorary secretary and organiser of the Women's Freedom League Settlement in Nine Elms, which provided daily penny and halfpenny hot meals for more than 100 children and operated a milk depot.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] Alfred Owen Broadley was born on 7 July 1868 in Greetland, Yorkshire, to Owen and Elizabeth Broadley.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] He was baptised on 6 September at St Thomas, Greetland.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] Broadley began his minister career with the Bible Christian Church at Salford from 1905 to 1917.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] He was assistant preacher to James Clark at Cross Lane Church in Salford.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] He worked as an engraver at Broad Oak Printworks.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] He was appointed minister at Haliwell Road Unitarian Church in Bolton from 1918 to 1922.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] He was minister of the Free Christian Church in Leicester and of Dover Unitarian Church from 1933 to 1939.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] He joined the Vegetarian Society in 1894 and became their lecturer in 1897.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] He advocated for a vegetarian diet consisting of whole bread, nuts, soups, omelettes, coffee and fruit.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] In 1912, Broadley was a speaker at Vegetarian Society meeting in Plymouth with Alfred B.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] He commented that he had been a vegetarian for 21 years which had made him a happier man without visit to a doctor.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] He also lectured on "Vegetarianism and the Higher Life", expounding the thesis that "any relationship to living creatures not based upon love, is contrary to conscience and will of God".
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] Broadley conducted the memorial service for William E.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] Axon's funeral at St Paul's Church, Kersal Moor in January 1913.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] He was a delegate of the Vegetarian Society to the Fourth Congress of the International Vegetarian Union in June 1913.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] Broadley was an opponent of vivisection.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] In 1923, he attended an anti-vivisection meeting with members from the British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection in Preston.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] Broadley died on 25 April 1939 from a heart attack at his residence in Dover, aged 70.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-o-broadley] His funeral was held at St James's Cemetery.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:a-o-broadley/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-w-duncan] He became a vegetarian as a young man through reading the work of T.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-w-duncan] Bailey Walker and joined the Vegetarian Society in 1877.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-w-duncan] He worked as an analytical chemist in Manchester and for James Woolley, Sons and Co., manufacture chemists.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-w-duncan] Duncan had studied with Carl Remigius Fresenius.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-w-duncan] He was also a Fellow of the Chemical Society.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-w-duncan] In 1884, Duncan authored a pamphlet *The Chemistry of Foods*.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-w-duncan] It was republished as *The Chemistry of Food and Nutrition* by the Vegetarian Society in 1905.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-w-duncan] Forward noted that Duncan had given "valuable aid to the Vegetarian Society in connection with the chemistry of food, and has contributed many useful essays and papers on the subject".
[src:a-o-broadley/a-w-duncan] Duncan was on the executive committee of the Vegetarian Society in 1880 and later served as a vice-president.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-w-duncan] In 1899, Duncan commented that "a grain of wheat contains everything that is required for nutrition and these constituents are in the right proportion, so that were it necessary we could live on wheatmeal bread and water alone".
[src:a-o-broadley/a-w-duncan] He later moved to New South Wales, Australia but remained in contact with vegetarians in England and was an officer for the Vegetarian Society in 1935.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-w-duncan] He married Annie Margaret Allison in 1890.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-w-duncan] They had two children: Frank and Phyllis.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-w-duncan] Duncan died in Punchbowl, New South Wales in 1946, aged 90.
[src:a-o-broadley/a-w-duncan] He was privately cremated at Rockwood crematorium.
